summary.seg:
Emmanuel College, MS 14 was probably copied in the 11th or 12th century, and is the first volume of a set of two (the second being Emmanuel MS 15). It contains 21 homilies by the Patriarch of Constantinople, John Chrysostom, In Matthaeum homiliae (48-68)
(Emmanuel MS 15 contains homilies 68-90). Emmanuel MSS 12-15, which all contain copies of Chrysostom's homilies on the Gospel of Matthew, share a common provenance and history, and were used by Frederick Field for his edition of the homilies (Cambridge 1839; see vol. 1, p. XVIII and XXI).

msItem.author: John Chrysostom
msItem.title: Homilies on the Gospel of St. Matthew 48-68
In Matthaeum homiliae 48-68
msItem.incipit: f. 1r ἡ δὲ καὶ συγκατασκευάζει τὸ δρᾶμα καὶ παγίδα τίθησι· καὶ αἰτεῖ χάριν σατανικήν
msItem.explicit: f. [144]v ἐγὼ δὲ ἐλεύθερος· καὶ ἐς ἐλευθέρων. δικαίους πόνους αἱρούμενος. οὐδὲ ὄναρ ταῦτα φαντασθῆναι δύναμαι
msItem.note: Defective at the beginning and the end.

list.item: Hom. 48: ff. 1r-5v (from PG 58, col. 489 line 43 to 494 line 50 κατ’ εἰκόνα Θεοῦ γενόμενον τύπτης)
Hom. 49: ff. [8]r-15v (from 497 line 4 τὸ δρᾶμα αὐτοὺς)
Hom. 50: ff. 15v-19r with lacuna: f. [17]v ends at 506 line 60 τὸν ἄνεμον ἐᾶ, f. [18]r starts from 508 line 51 πρᾶγμα βεβαιώσας
Hom. 62: ff. 101v-[104]v with lacuna: f. [102]v ends at 597 line 21 οὐκ ἀπὸ τῆς δημιουργίας, f. [103]r starts at 601 line 37 τούτων ἁπάντων ἠλευθερωμένα

support.material: Parchment (FHHF), of medium thickness and quality.

collation.p: The manuscript consists of 19 quires, all quaternia. The signatures indicate that a further two quires have been lost at the beginning of the manuscript.

list.item: Quire 18-4 ff. 1-[4] The first four folios have been lost, with loss of text.
Quire 38-2 ff. 15-[20] The fourth and fifth folios have been lost, with loss of text.
Quire 148-4 ff. 101-[104] The third-sixth folios have been lost, with loss of text.

signatures.p: Signatures in Greek numerals in brown ink on first recto, lower internal corner, from quire 3 (f. 15r) from εʹ to καʹ, continuing on Emmanuel MS 15.
Later signatures in Greek numerals in light-brown ink on the outer margins of the first recto and last verso of quires 14-19, numbered α-ε and 6 from f. 101r, continuing in Emmanuel MS 15.
Modern signatures in Greek numerals in pencil on first recto of quires 3-9 from εʹ to ιαʹ from f. 15r.

supportDesc.condition: There are holes in some folios (e.g. f. 1). There is some cockling and creasing, including pleating to f. [6]. There are drops of wax, areas of dirt and water staining, very extensive in the first few folios, which has contributed to some abrasion of text and transfer of ink to the facing page, particularly on ff. [4]v-5r.

layoutDesc.layout:
Two columns of 33 lines. 257 175
Pricking survives in the upper and lowre margins, but much has been lost to cropping. Ruled in hardpoint, system Leroy 1, type Leroy 44C2 . Text hangs from the lines.

handNote.p: The manuscript is written in a mixed minuscule script, upright or slanting slightly to the right, in brown and dark brown ink, pending from the ruling line. There is only moderate variation in letter size. Tails are occasionally flourished into the lower margins.
Syllabic abbreviations and superscription appear only at the ends of lines. Breathings are round and mute iota is not in use.
Punctuation used includes the middle and upper point and full stop.

decoDesc.decoNote: Headpiece outlined in red ink on f. 15v.
Initials in red ink for each homily.

additions.p: A notes on f. [iii] verso: A reference to the edition by Henry Savile, Sancti Ioannis Chrysostomi opera Graece, Eton College, 1612-13: Vide Editionem Sancti Chrysostomi Etonae impressam curante Henrico Savilio Anno MDCXII. Vol. 2. p. 113. l. 35 ἀλλὰ καὶ λίθων καὶ πάσης εὐκόλως κ.τ.λ.
A note of provenance on lower margin of f. 1r: απο το μοναστηρι του κασταμονητη.

binding.p: 18th-century full leather binding over millboards, sewn with cord on single raised supports, boards attached with laced-in slips Separate-sewn endbands, the outermost and the pastedowns of marbled paper. Hatched leather on the boards, with decorative gold tooling on boards and spine. The title Chrysostomi Homiliae Vol. III. MS is tooled in gold on black labels on the spine, and the classmark appears on patches.
binding.condition: The left outer joint is split at the tail, both endcaps are damaged and the tailband is starting to unravel. The leather covering has become flaky.

sealDesc.p: There are traces of a red wax seal on f. 1r.

accMat.p: Description slip from F. Field's edition (1839) pasted on f. [i] verso.

history.origin: The manuscript was copied in in the 11th or 12th century.
history.provenance:
The manuscript comes from the Monastery of Kastamoniti of Mount Athos (see notes on lower margin of f. 1r: απο το μοναστηρι του κασταμονητη). The manuscript was bought by
Anthony Askew (1722-1774) Askew, Anthony, 1722-1774, physician and book collector, in his travel to the Mt Athos. After his death, the manuscripts were sold by G. Leigh and J. Sotheby in the auction of his library in 1785 (Lot. n. 612), but his son
Adam Askew (1752-1844) Askew, Adam 1752-1844 was able to get possession of them again and gave them to
Samuel Parr (1747-1825) Parr, Samuel, 1747-1825 and eventually presented by him to Emmanuel College in 1814, as in the note on f. [iii] verso.

acquisition.p: Eventually presented to Emmanuel College by Samuel Parr in 1814.

recordHist.source: Description (2021) draws on M.R. James, The Western manuscripts in the library of Emmanuel College: a descriptive catalogue, Cambridge University Press, Cambridge, 1904, p. 12-13.
